author: Victor Reklaitis
title: By George, that royal baby really did shake up name trends
text:
If there were any doubts about whether the royals could make a name more popular, the latest U.K. data on baby names should put that to rest.
In the first full calendar year since the birth of Prince George of Cambridge, the name “George” has made a big move up. It rose three spots to No. 7, according to 2014 data released Monday on baby names in England and Wales.
No other top-10 name for boys advanced as much.
“George overtook William in the official rankings of most popular British baby names,” said a Telegraph article about the new data. Royal names continue to dominate at least boys’ names, with Harry staying in third place, that article added. Prince George was born in July 2013.
What about Princess Charlotte of Cambridge? William and Kate just welcomed her to the family in May 2015, so the newly released data can’t show a “Princess Charlotte effect” yet, as it only covers 2014.
Fans of “Frozen” will be happy to see Elsa is still on the rise, and “Game of Thrones” fans can see Stark girls are have an influence on girls’ names. Check out this post from the U.K. Office of National Statistics for more on how pop culture is shaping name trends.
Like Americans, Brits are increasingly partial to the name “Noah,” with the Telegraph noting the Biblical name has climbed 63 spots in a decade, though it’s not No. 1 for boys as it was in the U.S. last year.
Read more : This biblical name was the most popular for American boys last year
Oliver and Amelia held onto their No. 1 spots, as you can see in the table below showing last year’s top names in England and Wales.
